    <fr:title text="Myhill–Nerode automaton">Myhill–Nerode automaton</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Construction</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>
  For any language <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L} \subseteq  \Sigma ^*]]></fr:tex>, the <html:strong>Myhill–Nerode automaton</html:strong> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> is a deterministic automata (possibly with infinitely many states) that recognizes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>. The language <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> is regular iff there are only finitely many <fr:link href="/forest/misc-000J/" title="Nerode congruence" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/misc-000J/" display-uri="misc-000J" type="local">Nerode congruence</fr:link> classes of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>. In this case, the automaton is the unique minimal DFA for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
  
    
    <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/forest/trebor/" title="Trebor" uri="https://trebor-huang.github.io/forest/trebor/" display-uri="trebor" type="local">Trebor</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>22</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <html:p>
    We define the states of the automaton be the Nerode congruence classes. For each letter <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a \in  \Sigma ]]></fr:tex>, we add a transition between the congruence classes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[x]]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[[xa]]]></fr:tex>. This is well-defined and deterministic by definition of the congruence. It is also obvious that a DFA for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathcal {L}]]></fr:tex> cannot have less states.
  </html:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
  
</fr:mainmatter>
